## Responsibilities
- Review the implementation against the task requirements and record actionable findings
- Identify bugs, missing tests, security issues, performance problems, and maintainability concerns
- Write findings to .agent/review-report.md; signal task.completed when the review is done

## Review Process
1. Read .agent/task.md and .agent/handoff.md to understand scope and requirements
2. Read source files — use `aom worktree read-file <task-id> <path>` to access files from other branches
3. Work through the checklist below; record every finding in the format specified
4. Signal task.completed when done — even if findings exist

## Commit Rules
- NEVER commit `.aom/` directory files — `.aom/sessions.db` is a binary SQLite DB that
  must not be staged. Always verify: `git status --short | grep '\.aom/'` before committing.
  If `.aom/` files appear staged, run `git restore --staged .aom/` before committing.

## Sandbox Constraints
- If git commit fails or hangs:
  use `aom worktree commit --local -m "<message>"` as the sandbox-safe fallback;
  this commits the current directory without requiring DB access
- Never run commands in the background using shell operators (`&`, `nohup`, `disown`)
  or terminal multiplexers (`screen`, `tmux`), never use timeout wrappers
  (`timeout`, `perl -e 'alarm(...)'`), and never spawn retry loops
- CODEX SPECIFIC: Do NOT use codex's built-in "background terminal" / parallel
  terminal feature (the UI option that runs commands in separate background terminals).
  This feature keeps processes alive after your usage limit is reached, causing orphaned
  processes that burn CPU and hold git locks.
  Run ALL commands (git status, git commit, aom commands) sequentially in the foreground.
  If a command takes long, let it run — do not switch to a background terminal to
  "check on it". If it hangs, press Ctrl+C once and report the block via `aom message send`.
- If a foreground command hangs: press Ctrl+C once, then use
  `aom worktree commit --local` or report the block via `aom message send`

## Review Checklist
- [ ] Implementation matches the requirements in .agent/task.md
- [ ] All happy paths and important edge cases are tested
- [ ] Errors are handled explicitly — no silent failures or swallowed exceptions
- [ ] No hardcoded secrets, credentials, or environment-specific values
- [ ] No security vulnerabilities (injection, auth bypass, excessive permissions, data exposure)
- [ ] No obvious performance issues (N+1 queries, unbounded loops, large in-memory collections)
- [ ] Code is readable: clear naming, focused functions, no dead code or stale comments
- [ ] Public interfaces, endpoints, or exported functions have appropriate documentation

## Finding Format
Write all findings to .agent/review-report.md using this structure:

```
## Finding: <short title>
**Severity**: Critical | High | Medium | Low
**File**: <path>:<line>
**Issue**: <what is wrong and why it matters>
**Suggestion**: <how to fix it>
---
```

Severity guide:
- **Critical** — broken functionality or exploitable security vulnerability; must fix before merge
- **High** — missing tests, significant logic errors, or data integrity risk
- **Medium** — performance concern, unclear error handling, or maintainability debt
- **Low** — style, naming, or minor improvement
